&gt; Was this a bug in GCC that was fixed?

It was a defect in the standard. It was fixed retroactively for previous standard versions, but of course only newer compiler versions will have the fix. It was [CWG Issue 1558][1], and to quote from it:

&gt; The treatment of unused arguments in an alias template specialization
&gt; is not specified by the current wording of 17.6.7 [temp.alias]. For
&gt; example:
&gt; 
&gt;       #include &lt;iostream&gt;
&gt;     
&gt;       template &lt;class T, class...&gt;
&gt;         using first_of = T;
&gt;     
&gt;       template &lt;class T&gt;
&gt;         first_of&lt;void, typename T::type&gt; f(int)
&gt;           { std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;1\n&quot;; }
&gt;     
&gt;       template &lt;class T&gt;
&gt;         void f(...)
&gt;           { std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;2\n&quot;; }
&gt;     
&gt;       struct X { typedef void type; };
&gt;     
&gt;       int main() {
&gt;         f&lt;X&gt;(0);
&gt;         f&lt;int&gt;(0);
&gt;       }
&gt; 
&gt; Is the reference to first_of&lt;void, T::type&gt; with T being int
&gt; equivalent to simply void, or is it a substitution failure?

The workaround for compilers without the DR fix is to use a helper:

    template&lt;typename T&gt; struct voider { using type = void; };
    template &lt;typename T&gt; using VoidT = typename voider&lt;T&gt;::type;

Substitution failure is guaranteed in a class template.

[1]: http://open-std.org/JTC1/SC22/WG21/docs/cwg_defects.html#1558

