{
    public SubY_specialist f()
    {
        SubY_specialist y = new SubY_specialist();
        ...
        return y;
    }
}
```
3. Using the specialized type, and returning the specialized type. This is the &quot;essence&quot; of FRAUDVAN. `SubY_specialist` as the return type allows the user the flexibility to deal with the `SubY_specialist` returned, or alternatively use `f()` in terms of the interface `Y`. This is *incredibly common*, when interfaces are insufficiently specific to be used effectively (as they should be, since they&#39;re *abstract*). For example, in the Java [`Stream`][2] class, any time a method returns a `Stream`, this is happening. This is because `Stream` implements [`BaseStream`][3]. It *also* happens any time you take a `StringBuffer` and `reverse`, `append`, `replace`, `delete`, or `insert` (`StringBuffer` implements `CharSequence`).  
 &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; The reason this kind of behavior is needed is that interfaces often don&#39;t contain enough details to be utilized effectively by the end-user. Putting those details in interfaces would result in interface bloat/pollution, which is undesirable. Instead, directly having the class responsible for those details be used preserves the single responsibility principle for classes that have unique functionalities (avoiding being forced to implement redundancy in future implementers of the interface). After all, if your class implements two interfaces, you either have to create a new interface extending both those interfaces and return that (which can get ugly pretty quickly), or you can return the implementor, and have the end-user be responsible for which interface they need (not ugly).  
